Adjust rack to top position and preheat #oven{} to 425 degrees. Wash and dry
produce.

Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch-thick wedges. Toss on a #baking sheet{}
with a drizzle of oil, @dried oregano{1%teaspoon}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast
on top rack until browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

While potatoes roast, peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}. Quarter
@lemon{1}. Thinly slice @tomato{1} into rounds and season with salt and pepper.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{4%tablespoon}, @dijon mustard{2%teaspoon},
@sugar{1/4%teaspoon} (½ tsp for 4 servings), juice from one lemon wedge (two
wedges for 4), and a pinch of garlic. Season with salt and pepper to taste.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high
heat. Add @spinach{2.5%ounce} and remaining garlic; season with salt and pepper.
Cook, stirring, until spinach is wilted, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Transfer spinach to a second small bowl; stir in @cream cheese{2%tablespoon}
until combined.

Turn off heat. Wipe out pan.

Spread half the @sourdough bread{4%slice} slices with creamy spinach; top with
even layers of @feta cheese{1/2%cup}, @mozzarella cheese{1/2%cup}, and tomato.

Spread remaining sourdough slices with Dijonnaise (save some for serving).

Close sandwiches.

Melt @butter{1%tablespoon} in pan used for spinach over medium heat. Once hot,
add sandwiches and push around in pan until melted butter has absorbed.
Cook until bread is golden brown and cheese is slightly melted,
~{4-6%minutes}.

Add another @butter{1%tablespoon} to pan, then flip sandwiches and push around
again until melted butter has absorbed. Cook until bread is golden brown and
cheese is fully melted, ~{4-6%minutes}.

> TIP: If you have a heavy-bottomed pan, place on top of the sandwiches as they
> cook for a real panini experience!

Squeeze one lemon wedge over potatoes (two wedges for 4 servings).

Halve panini on a diagonal and divide between plates. Serve with potato wedges
and remaining Dijonnaise on the side for dipping.